# ðŸ“˜ Developer Guide: Implementing Engineering Skills

This is a private guide for managing the centralized engineering standards across projects.

## ðŸ”— Project Integration (Step-by-Step)

### 1. Linking the Standards
The most effective way to use the centralized `SKILLS.md` is via a **Git Submodule**. This ensures that if you update a skill in your "Standards Repo," you can pull it into all other projects.
```bash
git submodule add [https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/engineering-standards.git](https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/engineering-standards.git) docs/standards
2. Activating the AI
Ensure the IDE (Cursor/Windsurf) is aware of these files. The .cursorrules file in the project root should point directly to docs/standards/SKILLS.md.

3. Automated Enforcement (Husky)
To ensure the "Honest Coverage" and Security skills are followed, implement Husky hooks:

Pre-commit: Runs Linting and Zod schema checks.

Pre-push: Runs the full test suite. It must block the push if 80% global or 100% core coverage is not met.

ðŸ›  Working with the AI "Skills"
When working in the IDE, use "Skill Invocations" to save time and ensure accuracy:

Refactoring: "Apply the ArchitectureDesign skill to decouple this service from the database."

New Features: "Build a new extraction service using the ResilientLogic and SecurityDevSecOps skills."


UI/UX: "Review this form using the UniversalUX skill to ensure it meets WCAG 2.1 AA standards." 

ðŸ“ Maintenance
Update the master SKILLS.md in your standards repository whenever you encounter a new "Best Practice" or "Security Guardrail." This keeps your "Developer Brain" evolving.